Line 64 in D3D9Graphics.cpp fails to compile:

_declspec(dllexport) DWORD NvOptimusEnablement = 0x00000001;

Prepending another underscore solves the issue.

Quite large number of users use laptops which have dual graphics cards. By default if program is not recognised as a game it uses integrated intel hd card which gives poor performance. However, there is a way to force using nvidia high performance graphics on Windows. 

More info:
http://stackoverflow.com/questions/10535950/forcing-nvidia-gpu-programmatically-in-optimus-laptops

code to add somewhere in the source:

extern "C" {
    _declspec(dllexport) DWORD NvOptimusEnablement = 0x00000001;
}

A Simple Spline class designed as a component. 

Attach - Moves to the last point the parent node was attached to the spline or the start if Reset was called or no movement has occurred.
Detach - Detachs the parent node from the spline. Pauses all movement.
Reset - Resets the movement and detaches the node.
Move - Move the parent node to the next position of the spline.

The distance calculation is a little rough, anyone with better math than me please feel free to improve it, but it works at the moment.

 I decided not to lock down the implementation to Bezier Curves as I'll look into a Catmull-Rom implementation as well in the near future. Also Linear interpolation wasn't included directly as a Bezier Curve with only two points does the same thing.

Here's a very basic example of usage:

```
class Test : ScriptObject
{
    Spline@ spline;

    void Start()
    {
        @spline = node.GetComponent("Spline");

        spline.Push(Vector3(0,0,0));
        spline.Push(Vector3(0,0,100));
        spline.Push(Vector3(100,0,100));

        spline.Attach();
    }

    void Update(float timeStep)
    {
        spline.Move(timeStep);
    }
}
```

References #125.
